ce’s path, facing a resilient Morocco side, is a classic trap game; a slip here could derail their 19.8% title chance.\n\nCompared to previous World Cups, this 2026 tournament feels like a transition point. The dominance of South American teams is notably absent, with Argentina (15.6%) as the lone standard-bearer. The rise of Norway and the persistent strength of Belgium signal a shift toward European tactical evolution, where data-driven preparation and generational talent clusters are reshaping the map. Unlike the 2018 and 2022 tournaments, which were defined by a single dominant force (France, then Argentina), this edition feels wide open. The model suggests we are heading for a final where the winner will be the team that best blends star power with an unbreakable defensive structure—a recipe that currently favors Belgium, but leaves the door ajar for a Norwegian fairy tale."
